<div id="comment_64460057" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_64460057" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a id="comment_link_64460057" name="comment_link_64460057" href="//news.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23317663&amp;cid=64460057" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64460057)" >Re: SOLUBILITY !!</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64460057" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64460057); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>2</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~jovius">jovius</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~jovius">( 974690 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64460057"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64460057"><p>The CO2 effect does not saturate. The molecules are not inundated by photons, but they re-emit the energy. Molecules also collide with each other and distribute the energy. This means that the more CO2 there is in the atmosphere the bigger is the capacity to capture heat (radiation). The saturation is reached when the atmosphere cannot contain more CO2 molecules, if anything. A big chunk of the CO2 is dissolved into oceans too.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64460057">

</div>
</div>

